GODOLPHIN,Now that the peace with France has been made-
ANNE,Marlborough’s return back to England is imminent. I wonder Your Majesty whether it is right that he is left as head of our forces?
GODOLPHIN,He is a hero who won the peace for us!
HARLEY,Indeed. But he would have launched us into a bloody war that would have ruined us. So there’s that.
ANNE,We have made a poor peace that we will rue.
GODOLPHIN,"Well, our people are happy. I suggest, Queen Anne, that as a gesture of our graciousness to France perhaps he should be stood aside? A new era of peace and prosperity, a new day, a door to a new future, metaphors abound."
ANNE,It will look like we surrendered and the palace will be surrounded with men who lost eyes and arms in the war angry at this slight on their leader.
GODOLPHIN,Men with...
ANNE,They will stare in at us with rage.
GODOLPHIN,What a preposterous idea Godolphin. What are you-
ANNE,I...a...am tired...I will ponder it. Thank you all.
GODOLPHIN,"Your Majesty, may I broach the matter of Lady Marlborough?"
GODOLPHIN,No. You may not.
ANNE,"A breach in a dear friendship, surely this could be healed?"
ABIGAIL,Some wounds will not close. I have many such. One just walks around with them. Sometimes one can feel them filling with blood.
HARLEY,Quite. Lady Marlborough is a woman of passion. Perhaps she behaved rashly and is apologetic for her behaviors?
ABIGAIL,You know this?
ABIGAIL,I... believe it to be so.
HARLEY,Her love and loyalty to you and this country are her reasons for living. Perhaps she could write you and we could attempt to repair at least one wound in our Queen?
ABIGAIL,I cannot stop her. I would imagine it is pointless and I would dash the letter into the fire. But... I cannot stop her.
HARLEY,Shut up please. SHUT UP!
ABIGAIL,A moment.
HARLEY,We will reconvene with some order and grace after lunch.
ANNE,I cannot control them. Whining for more.
ABIGAIL,Marlborough will return soon. THE FAVOURITE SHOOTING SCRIPT 6 MAR 17 96.
ANNE,"What is that to me? Your politics is dreary Harley. I have what I want, you have what you want. Our business is done."
ABIGAIL,If Marlborough remains head of our forces she has every right to be at court. Even if she is at odds with the Queen.
ABIGAIL,I see.
ANNE,I imagined you would. The Queen and her must not have the opportunity to repair this wedge between them. For if they do I pity what Lady Marlborough will make of you. If there was some gentle nudge you might provide to the Queen’s cogitations on this issue.
ABIGAIL,Are you sure this is all the mail?
ANNE,You seek something?
ABIGAIL,No. A...fabric piece from my cousin in Florence.
ANNE,I’m sure it will come.
ABIGAIL,Everyone is on the bed. Shall I join?
ANNE,Of course.
ABIGAIL,I am in a quandary and you are my dearest one. I do not know whether to speak of...
ANNE,What is it?
ABIGAIL,I will... I am not sure.
ANNE,"I do not like this, you will lodge this unknowable thing in my brain and it will eat me with horrible possibilities."
ABIGAIL,It is not horrible dear Anne. It is just money.
ANNE,Money?
